        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=59361&TOPIC_ID=7396&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Gears+that+reduce+downtime&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>


        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">> +HP is an excellent thing to go into <BR>> because you can lich the hp to mana and <BR>> then regain during fight.  HP = Mana.</P><P>This really isn't all that true, and I don't know why people always repeat it.</P><P>Like Snag said, the total amount of HP you have has absolutely no effect on how fast you regain mana. You lich hitpoints at a set rate. You get mana at a set rate. You have to spend a set amount of mana to get a set amount of hitpoints back.</P><P>Thus, if you lich down 500 hitpoints in a fight, it doesn't MATTER if your max hp is 2000, 1500, or 1000. You still have to spend the same amount of mana to get your health back up.</P><P>Having more HP does precisely two things: lets you take one or two more hits before dying, and lets you wait longer before you are forced to lifetap to stay alive. Over time, a higher HP cap won't make you any more efficient.. you have to spend the same amount of mana to keep health up no matter what you do.</P><P>So all that truly matters is mana regen and health regen.</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

